GERMANY : A Costly Budgetary Idol
FRAUCHE - The European Central Bank (ECB) is facing fierce attacks in Germany, a country that has long prided itself on defending the principle of central bank independence.
It was actually Germany that insisted this principle be included among the criteria set out by the Maastricht Treaty, which lays down the conditions for membership in the European Monetary Union.
For many members of the Economic and Monetary Union (EMU), the decision to grant independence to their central bank in order to join the eurozone implied a political regime change.
Thus, the independence of the Banque de France during the 1992 referendum on the Maastricht Treaty was one of the strongest arguments in the campaign against adopting the euro.
In today's Germany, it has become commonplace, if one can say so, to put pressure on the central bank.
For several months now, even the Minister of Finance, Wolfgang Schäuble, has regularly commented on the monetary policy of the European Central Bank (ECB).
Schaüble's interventions target the very core of what constitutes the independence of the central bank.
Although he does not seek to redefine the objective of monetary policy (that 'price stability,' in the old Bundesbank jargon), he nonetheless offers advice on the tools the ECB should use and how they should be handled to achieve such a goal.
We know of precedents.
In 1998, Oskar Lafontaine, then Germany's Minister of Finance, gave his advice to the first president of the ECB, Wim Duisenberg, on how to conduct monetary policy (Lafontaine's goal was to ultimately create a targeted zone for exchange rates).
Duisenberg, with typically Dutch laconicism, replied that it was not incongruous for a politician to express an opinion on monetary policy (in Germany, this was absolutely unusual). "Yet," he added, "it would be entirely abnormal to take account of [his] suggestions."

Maintaining the independence of monetary policy has long been a central element of Germany's Stabilitätkultur (culture of stability).
The founding act of the Bundesbank's reputation for strict independence was its refusal to yield to Chancellor Konrad Adenauer's exhortations in 1956 to contain the rise in interest rates.
At that time, France did not see things the same way.
Charles de Gaulle was about to create the Fifth Republic, with the Banque de France reporting to the Minister of Finance.
But it was another time.
Following various crises that shook the ERM, monetary policy has increasingly tended to replace fiscal policy.
Has the old dogma become obsolete?
The European Union remains highly vulnerable; the median EU citizen has already lost ten years, and what is even more alarming, we are getting close to the critical situation.
The United States, however, are doing better.
Despite a difficult-to-manage political blockage, they have managed to address the macro-economic problem (the weakness of global demand) by launching expansionary fiscal and monetary policies.
The US also handled their banking problems better, which were initially much more severe than in Europe.
(There is of course a strong interaction between the measures that can be taken in both areas.
More robust an economy is, more profitable its banks are, and more capable they are of fulfilling their function: financing the economy.)
But the independence of the ECB is less threatened by sound advice from a finance minister than by the lack of support from the population.
In fact, the famous autonomy of the Bundesbank relied less on its legal status than on the unshakeable support (justified by its performance) of German citizens.
It is exactly the opposite with the ECB.
Voice is being raised, notably in Germany, calling for subjecting it to greater pressure.
But the greatest threat to the ECB's autonomy lies in the unbearable burden that weighs upon its shoulders.
The less budgetary policy is called upon to stabilize production, the more factually central banks are constrained to take on this objective (unless, of course, they are designed to let nature take its course and allow the economy to get stuck in stagnation, or worse).
The political result of this chain of events is a very clear regression towards nationalism, both right and left, in all UEM countries, including Germany.
The rise of nationalism is almost a logical corollary of the policies pursued.
It is endogenous.
And there too, Germany leads the dance, with its obsession with schwarze Null, budget balance, come rain or shine.
In Germany, budget deficits are viewed poorly, not only numerically but also morally, even though this defies economic sense and seems like clientelism.
At the end of the 19th century, the leading German public finance experts, such as Albert Schäffle and Adolph Wagner, crafted a "golden rule" according to which recurrent expenditures should be financed, on average, by recurrent revenues.
Public expenditures, and the resources they require, justify themselves by their usefulness.
This amounts to saying that investments aimed at improving productivity – capital expenditures – can be financed with debt, whose repayment is secured by the growth in revenues and the tax base associated with those revenues.
This classical line of conduct has been institutionalized in a useful concept: the distinction between current expenses and investment expenses, which is still practiced at the municipal level in Germany (and in Austria).
This is crucial because in Germany, about 50% of public sector investment spending is managed at this level (the proportion has decreased, as the municipal share was two-thirds at the beginning of the 1990s).
These expenditures are consistent with support for the competitiveness of German small and medium-sized enterprises (the Mittelstand).
However, compared to the early 1990s and in constant prices, investment spending has fallen by about 15%.
For more than a decade, they have been insufficient for maintaining the capital stock.
If this is not how we prepare for the future, then this is how we undermine productivity and prosperity.
In brief, the schwarze Null goes against the intended goal.
Outdated infrastructure (though not as severely as in the United States) has become a real problem for Germany.
Furthermore, the fiscal frugality of German leaders extends beyond Germany's borders, and its effects are amplified by the monetary union, which lacks exchange rates to accommodate national particularisms.
Naturally, the European monetary union is imperfect.
But blaming the only institution willing to « do what it takes » to get the eurozone back on track is a very bad idea.
For countries to use, where it exists, their budgetary space to reduce pressure on the ECB would be a much better strategy.
Germany, without a doubt, enjoys a certain degree of maneuvering room in this regard.
